post_text: Click to watch video from Friday's Patriot Day ceremony at the Veterans' Memorial Building in downtown Hollister. San Benito High School's ASB Commissioners of Culture and Climate, Sydney Yamanishi and Adriana Omar, connected with Maria Spandri of the VFW to coordinate this event. Hollister FFA did a flag display and had a tribute to Captain Jason Dahl. The Hollister Fire Department, VFW, Hollister Police Department, and the Sheriff's Department were in attendance and all participated in the short ceremony. The National Anthem was sung by Jenny Mendolla Arbizu from the San Benito Stage Company, followed by a 15-gun salute and "Taps" played by Eric Spandri.

post_text: In honor of Patriot Day (Sept. 11), the Hollister Veterans of Foreign Wars partnered with San Benito High School's Associated Student Body and Hollister FFA on a 9/11 tribute in front of the Veterans' Memorial Building in downtown Hollister. Local first responder agencies were also invited to the ceremony, at which "Taps" was played at 8:46 a.m. FFA placed flags and replicas of the Twin Towers in the courtyard in honor of those who perished as a result of the terrorist attacks in 2001.

post_text: The power at San Benito High School was unexpectedly shut down today at 2:43 p.m., which in turn shut down all computer servers on campus. We will start turning the servers back on at 4 p.m., which will take approximately 45 minutes to restore network and wifi access to the site.

post_text: San Benito High School staff are finding innovative ways to support students.
shared_text:
Captain
September 2 at 2:18 PM ¬∑

San Benito High School Speech Therapists Natalia Silva-Sepulveda and Brianna Teimoorian, along with Transition Teacher Breanna Brooks and support staff have created a set of popsicle stick icons as visual support for students during distance learning. They have made sets for teachers, administrators, and are working on making enough for our instructional aides as well - who push into Zoom classrooms. The visuals come in handy while working 1:1 with a student or with a whole class. Ms. Brooks utilizes the mute and unmute icons daily with her students.

For students who need support, they are able to see the icon and match it to one of the icons on the screen. For example, if a student has a difficult time navigating to google classroom, the teacher holds up the google classroom icon, the student is able to visualize the icon and locate it on the screen without additional prompting!
text:
San Benito High School staff are finding innovative ways to support students.

Captain
September 2 at 2:18 PM ¬∑

San Benito High School Speech Therapists Natalia Silva-Sepulveda and Brianna Teimoorian, along with Transition Teacher Breanna Brooks and support staff have created a set of popsicle stick icons as visual support for students during distance learning. They have made sets for teachers, administrators, and are working on making enough for our instructional aides as well - who push into Zoom classrooms. The visuals come in handy while working 1:1 with a student or with a whole class. Ms. Brooks utilizes the mute and unmute icons daily with her students.

For students who need support, they are able to see the icon and match it to one of the icons on the screen. For example, if a student has a difficult time navigating to google classroom, the teacher holds up the google classroom icon, the student is able to visualize the icon and locate it on the screen without additional prompting!

post_text: With Monday‚Äôs announcement that the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) will allow summer meal program operators to continue serving free meals to all children into the Fall months, San Benito High School will continue to provide free breakfast and lunch meals to anyone 18 years old or younger, regardless of whether they are an SBHS student. The USDA said the extension, which runs through Dec. 31, 2020, ‚Äúwill help ensure ‚Äì no matter what the situation is on-the-ground ‚Äì children have access to nutritious food as the country recovers from the COVID-19 pandemic.‚Äù SBHS Food Service Supervisor Jim Lewis said that, because of the waiver, he and his crew will continue disbursing meals to the community from the Baler Alley location between 10 a.m. and 1 p.m. Monday through Friday. ‚ÄúWe look forward to serving our neighbors and offering them nutritious meals for their students and children to help keep them fueled for learning and growing,‚Äù Lewis said.

In advance of Patriot Day on Sept. 11, San Benito High School's ASB (Associated Student Body) is asking our community to share their memories and experiences of 9/11 and how it impacted their life. The videos, a minute or two in length through the website Flipgrid (linked below), can address your reflections of that day, what you were doing when you heard the news, etc. If you would prefer instead to contribute a written response, please email them to Catalina Lemos at clemos@sbhsd.k12.ca.us. SBHS ASB members will do their best to include excerpts of as many reflections/remembrances as possible in the final compilation, which will be shared out for Patriot Day, which San Benito High School annually observes to honor and remember those who lost their lives or were injured during the attacks of September 11, 2001.

post_text:
As part of its energy conservation and renewable program on campus, San Benito High School has achieved a total savings of more than $516,000 and reduced electrical consumption by 2,313 MWh as of June 2020. The decreased electrical consumption translates to the following green equivalencies:
- removing 220 cars from the road
- preserving 31,360 trees from deforestation
- powering 157 American homes

post_text: A message from San Benito High School Food Service Manager Jim Lewis: "Starting Monday, Aug. 31, we will begin serving under the National School Lunch Program, which will limit us to providing meals for San Benito High School students only. When picking up meals for your student, you must have their ID number so that we can record them as receiving a meal. Meals will be charged according to your current application results (Free, Reduced or Full Pay. Full pay meals are $1.50 for breakfast and $3 for lunch.) Have a wonderful weekend and we will see you in Baler Alley between 10 a.m. and 1 p.m. on Monday. Remember, we hand out meals Monday through Friday."

post_text: San Benito High School's auto shop is willing to pay $$$ for your higher mileage used vehicle. Specifically, the program needs 2010 or newer small Toyota, Honda, Hyundai, Ford, or Chevy sedans that are in decent shape: No broken glass, badly damaged sheet metal or torn up interiors. SBHS Auto Instructor Tom Agan said, "We need vehicles that run and drive, but won't pass smog. These vehicles are extremely helpful to help teach our auto students! You can also donate your vehicle (if approved by the high school administration) and take a tax deduction." Please contact Mr. Agan via email at tagan@sbhsd.k12.ca.us

Good Morning Balers, Parents, and Guardians,

Today and every Wednesday will be a day of two Zoom sessions for all students. The first Zoom is for both AM and PM students for Block 1 (This is a student's Monday and Thursday class). It starts at 10:15 a.m. and lasts until 11. It is okay to login early.

The second Zoom is for both AM and PM students for Block 2 (This is a student's Tuesday and Friday class). It starts at 11:15 a.m. and lasts until noon.

See the image below for details on Wednesday's instructional schedule. A reminder that asynchronous learning time is when students will work independently on assignments. Synchronous learning is Zoom instructional time.

text: Distribution of the 2019-2020 San Benito High School yearbook continues this week, with pick-up events in the Andy Hardin Stadium parking lot Monday through Wednesday from 3:30-5:30 p.m. Monday's event is for the Class of 2021 only. Tuesday is for the Class of 2022 (and '21 if they couldn't make it Monday) and Wednesday is for the Class of 2023 and any other classes. SBHS 2020 grads who were unable to pick up their senior items and yearbooks last Friday may do so at any of this week's distribution days.

post_text: A reminder that because of the Governor's mandate that schools will be closed for in-person instruction as long as the county in which they operate remains on the monitoring list for COVID-19 cases, San Benito High School will be unable to host either the ACT or SAT until San Benito County is removed from the monitoring list and is able to safely reopen for students. At this time, San Benito County is on the monitoring list and will begin the school year utilizing a full remote instructional model. College Board is in the process of sending communication to the test takers regarding a refund.

post_text: From the SBHSD Food Services Department: During remote instruction, we remain committed to bringing our students their favorite food selections that they previously could enjoy daily at any of our fine eating establishments here on campus. We are working with Domino's Pizza so that we can bring this product to our students weekly, and we will also be featuring our "House Made" selections that have proven to be student favorites so that they can experience the mouth-watering flavors of SBHSD while at home. These selections, available for pick up from 10 a.m. to noon in Baler Alley Monday through Friday, will be served hot and ready to eat for convenience and provide students with the fuel they need to get the most out of their studies. It is our mission and commitment to bring our students the best in taste and service.

post_text:
San Benito High School wants to extend an apology to all parents and students for any inconvenience and long wait times during Tuesday‚Äôs Chromebook, textbook and schedule handout events around campus. We are also sorry that not all parents and students who were in line were able to pick up their items.
Faced with the ongoing challenging circumstances we all face during the pandemic and move to remote learning, this was the first time that we have handed out Chromebooks, textbooks and schedules all at once to all students, while working to ensure that social distancing protocols were followed. Utilizing all available resources, our staff members worked to serve every student, but because that did not happen, we again apologize and pledge to do our best to improve the process for Wednesday‚Äôs distribution.

post_text: A message to freshmen and other new students from San Benito High School Principal Adrian Ramirez: "We have recently mailed out a document to all new students, with instructions on how to activate their school issued Gmail accounts. It is critical that all new students activate their Gmails, no later than August 11. Students' school issued Gmails will be one of the main sources of information regarding the start of our school year. Included in the mailer are also details regarding our Freshman Orientation, which will occur virtually. Any incoming 9th grader that was already issued a school Gmail account during our recent summer school program does not have to activate their account again."

post_text: San Benito High School alumnus Mason Marquez (pictured at the far right) of U.C. Santa Barbara baseball was named to the the Big West Conference's Winter/Spring Academic All-Conference Team, the league announced Thursday. To earn Big West All-Academic status, students must maintain a 3.0 cumulative grade point average, complete one full academic year at the institution prior to the season for which the award is being given, and compete in at least 50% of the team's contests.

post_text: San Benito High School has set up two drop boxes in Baler Alley for textbook returns. These boxes are always open and emptied frequently. In addition, the textbook room is open on Tuesdays and Thursdays from 8 a.m. to noon and 1 to 4 p.m. to check in books directly. Remember, outstanding fines will prevent students from receiving diplomas, transcripts, yearbooks, work permits and sports participation.

post_text: A message from San Benito High School College and Career Center Specialist Mary Andrade: "I am reaching out to you in hopes of your support for the local fundraiser for the VFW 9242 Scholarship. Our local VFW awarded 10 students this past year with a total of $10,000. Due to the pandemic, they were unable to host their annual golf tournament that funds these scholarships for our students. I am asking for your support, if possible, this year by purchasing a $20 raffle ticket. Please open the attachments and review all the wonderful prizes available."

post_text: The San Benito High School Board of Trustees this week adopted an equity statement as a board policy, which notes "San Benito High School has an obligation to provide all students with the access and opportunities necessary for college, career, and life success. This requires that our school leaders address and abolish practices, policies, and barriers that perpetuate inequities which lead to opportunity and achievement gaps." The full equity statement is attached.

post_text:
Due to Coronavirus (COVID-19), children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals at school will get extra food benefits, called Pandemic EBT or P-EBT benefits. P-EBT benefits help families in California buy food when schools are closed because of the coronavirus emergency.

Families will get up to $365 per eligible child on their P-EBT card to use on food and groceries.

Families with children who get CalFresh, Medi-Cal or Foster Care benefits do not need to apply. Most will get their P-EBT card in the mail during the month of May. P-EBT cards began arriving around May 12.

Families with children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals and who did not get their P-EBT card in the mail by about May 22 must apply online before June 30. The online application is available at https://ca.p-ebt.org/en/

post_text: The San Benito County Public Health Department has notified San Benito High School that athletic conditioning and workouts may resume with a 12 to 1 student/coach ratio on Monday, June 22 at SBHSD outdoor athletic facilities. The attached letter contains the guidelines that must be followed to ensure the safety of student-athletes and staff. Also attached is the document that parents must sign in order for their student to participate. Students must submit this form to their cohort coach upon screening into the first conditioning session for their sport. This form will also be available on the SBHS Athletics website. The attached slides provide information on what student-athletes can and should do regarding paperwork for the upcoming season, offer a list of coach contacts for Fall sports (students should contact coaches to get on lists), information about Cheer (which now expects to have tryouts in July), and provides contact info for Athletics Clerk Becky Doty.

Poteat Scholarship from the National Technical Honor Society (NTHS). Kasandra was inducted into NTHS based on her outstanding performance in her Career and Technical Education classes. She plans on attending Hartnell Community College to study nursing.

post_text:
San Benito High School is aware of the ‚Äúpositive demonstration march‚Äù scheduled for Saturday, June 6 in the football stadium parking lot on San Benito Street. While the event is not affiliated with SBHS, we do support participants‚Äô rights to express their views in a safe and positive manner. To that end, the District has been in consistent communication with the organizers of the march, Hollister Black Lives Matter Team, along with San Benito County Sheriff‚Äôs Capt. Eric Taylor and Interim Hollister Police Chief Carlos Reynoso, a Baler alumnus. We appreciate all parties‚Äô communication and efforts to ensure that the march goes safely and smoothly. San Benito High School supports the march organizers‚Äô goal to raise awareness and communicate the need for change.
We thank our community law enforcement agencies for their ongoing collaboration to keep everyone safe. SBHS staff will join them in the parking lot to help ensure a safe start to the march.

post_text: The San Benito High School yearbook is scheduled to arrive on campus in early July, so distribution plans will be announced over the next month or so to ensure that everyone who orders a book receives one. The 324-page book was completed before the transition to distance learning, so it includes all of the traditional sections (student life, clubs, academics, people and athletics -- including spring sports), plus a special, four-page insert addressing the COVID-19 pandemic. If you haven't yet ordered your copy, they will remain on sale until sold out online through YearbookOrderCenter.com (just enter code 6779 to select SBHS). Students who bought a Baler Pak at the start of the school year already have a book reserved in their name.

post_text: A message from San Benito High School Food Services Director Jim Lewis: "Today, the crew assembled and handed out 3,600 breakfast and 3,600 lunch meals. This week, we will be handing out bags containing three breakfast and lunch meals each. This will carry the students through Monday, May 25 (Memorial Day) as we will not be serving that day but will return on Wednesday, May 27 to once again distribute sack meals. The meals distributed on May 27 will also contain three meals to sustain through the weekend, after which we will return to our regular Monday and Wednesday serving schedule. We thank everyone for their continued support of our efforts."

post_text: San Benito High School's inaugural "Rock the Mock" event, which provides an opportunity for students to engage in an unofficial interview while learning life skills needed to obtain employment, moved to an online format through Google Classroom and is beginning today (Friday, May 15). SBHS juniors and seniors who signed up will participate in workshops and watch videos and presentations prior to participating in virtual mock interviews. "We have eager and waiting community members who will be conducting mock interviews for our students who volunteer," said Rock the Mock organizer Vanessa Klauer, San Benito High School's Career/Job Training Coordinator.

post_text:
San Benito High School senior Ariana Fabian, who will attend St. John's University in New York, shares the story of meeting her mentor and how she decided to pursue a career in public administration. She writes: "After college, I hope to come back to my community and work to maintain responsible growth without taxing our resources. No longer the stranger in my town, I want to be one of its leaders."

https://leadership.acsa.org/meeting-the-mentor-that-shaped-my-life

post_text: A message from San Benito High School Food Services Manager Jim Lewis: "Today, the team assembled 1,200 breakfast and 1,200 lunch sack meals for distribution, for a total of 2,400 meals. The all-inclusive weekly total is 9,350 meals provided. Next week, the team will be packing and distributing meals on Monday and Wednesday only. On Wednesday, we will package three breakfast and lunch meals to carry through the remainder of the week. Thank you to everyone for their continued support. We are cutting back distribution to two days to help support the shelter-in-place efforts and keep our workers and the community safe. Thank you for your understanding."
